data.content:
Here's what happened and how to fix it:

**Root cause:** C# 14 introduces new built-in span conversions. In your expression tree, `array.Contains(num)` now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent `Span<T>`-based methods, so this throws at runtime.

**Fix options** — force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three prevent the span overload from being selected. Pick whichever reads best in your codebase — option 3 is the most explicit.
